ummary":"当Sir Richard Plunket于1339年出生在爱尔兰庫迪 米亞斯拉雷根时，他的父亲John Plunket24岁，母亲Alice de Trim25岁。他于1369年与Margaret Plunkett在爱尔兰迪 本 米亞斯结婚。他们至少是2个儿子的父母。他于1388年在爱尔兰被列为lord high chancellor of ireland。他去世于1388年在他的家乡享年49岁。"},"hr":{"1339–1388":"1339.–1388.","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339.–preminula","1370–1445":"1370.–1445","1372–Male":"1372.–preminuo","–Male":"preminuo","1315–1352":"1315–1352.","1315–Female":"1315–preminula","1315":"1315","1369":"1369.","1445":"1445","1388":"1388.","1352":"1352.","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372.","1370":"1370.","about 1372":"oko 1372.","1339":"1339.","County Louth, Ireland":"County Louth, Irska","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Irska","Ireland":"Irska","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Irska","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irska","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irska"},"cs":{"1339–1388":"1339–1388","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339–Zesnulá","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Zesnulý","–Male":"Zesnulý","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315–Female":"1315–Zesnulá","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"okolo 1372","1339":"1339","County Louth, Ireland":"County Louth, Irsko","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Irsko","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irsko","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irsko"},"da":{"1339–1388":"1339–1388","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339–Afdød","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315–Female":"1315–Afdød","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"omkring 1372","1339":"1339","County Louth, Ireland":"County Louth, Irland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Irland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irland","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irland"},"nl":{"1339–1388":"1339–1388","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339–Overleden","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315–Female":"1315–Overleden","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"circa 1372","1339":"1339","County Louth, Ireland":"County Louth, Ierland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Ierland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ierland","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ierland"},"en":{"1339–1388":"1339–1388","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339–Deceased","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"about 1372","1339":"1339","County Louth, Ireland":"County Louth, Ireland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Plunket","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Irish: variant of   Plunkett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Plunkett","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a metathesized form of Plouquenet in Ille-et-Villaine, Brittany, so named from Breton <i>plou</i> ‘parish’ (from Latin <i>plebs</i> ‘people’) + <i>Guenec</i>, the personal name (a diminutive of <i>guen</i> ‘white’) of a somewhat obscure saint. As an Irish name, it has been Gaelicized as <b>Pluincéid</b>."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Plunket was born in 1339, in Rathregan, County Meath, Ireland, his father, John Plunket, was 24 and his mother, Alice de Trim, was 25. He married Margaret Plunkett in 1369, in Diocese of Meath, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. In 1388, at the age of 49, his occupation is listed as lord high chancellor of ireland in Ireland. He died in 1388, in his hometown, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1339–1388":"1339–1388","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339–Surnud","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"umbes 1372","1339":"1339","County Louth, Ireland":"County Louth, Iirimaa","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Iirimaa","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Iirimaa","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1339–1388":"1339–1388","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339–Kuollut","1370–1445":"1370–1445","1372–Male":"1372–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1315–1352":"1315–1352","1315–Female":"1315–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1370":"1370","about 1372":"noin 1372","1339":"1339","County Louth, Ireland":"County Louth, Irlanti","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlanti","Rathmore, County Meath, Ireland":"Rathmore, County Meath, Irlanti","Rathregan, Meath, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irlanti","Of, Rathregan, Meath, Ireland":"Rathregan, County Meath, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1339–1388":"1339–1388","1340–1374":"1340–1374","1339–Female":"1339–Décédée","1370–1445":"1370–1445